My hope is that by providing this feedback tool I am able to react to your comments during the course so you and other currently enrolled students can benefit.

    • EXTRA CREDIT ASSIGNMENTS

      • The Upside of Irrationality Extra Credit Assignments

        You have the ability to earn extra credit by reading The Upside of Irrationality by Dan Ariely. It looks at how our behavior sometimes deviates from what is predicted by the standard economic model we will be discussing and using in this class. The first (Introductory) chapter is due on September 3rd.

      • Chapter 1 (For Those Waiting for Their Textbook) URL

      • STUDENT RESOURCES

      • NY Times: Does the SIze of the Incentive Matter? URL
      • NYTimes: Does the Size of the Incentive Matter? File
      • The Surprising Truth About What Motivates Us (10:47)[CC] URL

      • Optional Resources

      • Opportunity Cost -- NPR Radio Lab: Playing God (8/21/16) URL

        When people are dying and you can only save some, how do you choose? Maybe you save the youngest. Or the sickest. Maybe you even just put all the names in a hat and pick at random. Would your answer change if a sick person was standing right in front of you?

      • Buying Time, Not Stuff (5:44)[Transcript] URL

        An interesting article on how using money to free up your time makes people happier than using money to buy more stuff.

      • Perverse Incentives: Pedestrian Scam in Russia URL
        Apparently, drivers in Russia are legally bound to compensate pedestrians for any accident, no matter who is at fault.  The law's unintended consequence is that pedestrians deliberately try to get hit by cars.  Russian drivers are now using dashboard cameras to avoid lawsuits.


      • Marginal Analysis Applied to NFL Fourth Downs URL

        A study analyzed the behavior of NFL coaches on fourth down and whether a team should attempt to make a first down.  This analysis on marginal thinking has been met with some skepticism. 

      • The Onion: Nation Just Wants to Be Safe, Happy, Comfortable, Entertained at All Times (8/1/13) URL
        In this The Onion spoof, six mock interviewees describe what they want in order to be happy. As you'll see, every American wants to be safe, happy, rich and comfortable -- they have virtually unlimited wants.
      • Planet Money: Making Christmas More Joyful, and More Efficient (12/21/10)(19:32)[Transcript] URL

        We go into a seventh-grade classroom and give a bunch of kids some small gifts candy, raisins, fig newtons. Then we ask them how much they value what they got, and if they can think of a way to make everyone better off, without buying any more gifts. They quickly arrive at a solution: trade.

        [Transcript]Opens in new window


      • Video: Trade-Offs in Green Day's "Good Riddance" (Time of our Lives) (2:31)[CC] Page

        "Good Riddance" is about the moments in life when we are faced with choices.  As an economic decision maker, what should you do when you come to a "fork in the road?" Use Amara CC for closed captions.

      • Video: Opportunity Cost in Sheryl Crow's "Soak up the Sun" (3:50)[CC] Page

        "Soak Up the Sun" deals with the opportunity cost of sunning oneself while the world goes by.  The idea of trying to catch rays while they are still "free" makes an economist wonder -- does Ms. Crow understand there is no such thing as a free sunbeam? Use Amara CC for closed captions.

      • Video: Scarcity in Seinfeld "The Sponge" - 1 clip (1:10)[CC] Page
      • Video: Scarcity in Seinfeld "The Sponge" - clip 2 (0:46)[CC] Page

        Elaine's favorite birth control sponge is being pulled off the market, so she buys a case of Today sponges and carefully scrutinizes her dates for their sponge-worthiness. A nice illustration of scarcity, opportunity cost, and trade-offs. Use Amara CC for closed captions on both clips.

      • Opportunity Cost & Gains from Trade in The Office Garage Sale (7:45)[CC] URL

        The Office has a garage sale with everybody bringing their unwanted items.  Dwight trades his way up from a thumbtack to a telescope (and ultimately a bag of magical beans).  Shows gains from trade, the opportunity cost of decisions and how effective marketing can increase the demand for a product.

      • Video: Opportunity Cost & Trade-Offs in Saving Private Ryan (2:37)[CC] Page

        Saving Private Ryan is different than most war movies in that the calculus of war is different; the mission is to save a single man since all three of his brothers were killed and the general believes the family has sacrificed enough.  The opportunity cost of the mission is includes the lives that the patrol loses. Use Amara CC for closed captions.

      • Supply and Demand Practice Problems File

      • Optional Resources

      • Chapter 3 Interactive Scratch Paper Page
      • Chapter 3 Office Hours Video Tutorials (5 videos)[No CC] Page
      • Video: Smart Car Supply and Demand Example (2:51)[Amara CC] Page
      • The Hudsucker Proxy Movie -- Change in D or QD (3:11)[No Dialogue] URL

        This movie chronicles the introduction of the hula hoop.  When it was first introduced, it was not particularly popular.  They keep lowering the price in hopes of increasing sales.  It isn't until a boy happens upon a hula hoop and is seen by a large group of school kids that the hula hoop becomes popular.  Think about these events in terms of a change in quantity demanded versus a change in demand.

      • Video: Pawn Stars -- Finding an Equilibrium (2:01)[CC] URL

        This clip from Pawn Stars illustrates how the forces of supply and demand work to find an equilibrium.  It shows some customers that know what price range to expect and quickly come to an agreement and those whose desired price is much higher than the offer. 

      • The Economics of Sex URL
        An article and video (9:56)[CC] using supply and demand analysis to discuss how the price of sex has changed over time.


      • Sip Slowly: an international pub crawl in search of the world's most expensive cocktails URL

        An article about the most expensive cocktails in the world.  For the "Ritz Side Car," the high price results from an extremely limited supply of a key ingredient (input).

      • Chapter 4 Interactive Scratch Paper Page

      • Video: Elasticity in Beyonce's Irreplaceable (4:13)[Amara CC] Page

        Is Beyonce's demand for her boyfriend elastic or inelastic?  In the song, she tells her ex-boyfriend that she already has another boyfriend; thus, he is replaceable.  The lyrics suggest that her demand for her ex-boyfriend is elastic.

      • Video: Elasticity in Shawshank Redemption (2:48)[Amara CC] Page

        This is  a nice illustration of how a black market could work.  Since Andy's demand is inelastic, he pays a premium to get a small rock hammer used by rock hounds.  He intends to use the pick to dig out.  Since getting caught with this pick is risky, the agreed upon price is much higher than it would be if the purchase was made outside of jail.

      • Chapter 5 Office Hour Videos [CC] Page
      • Video: How Changes in Demand and Supply Affect Surplus (5:59)[Amara CC] Page
      • Video: Reviewing Tax Revenue, Incidence and Deadweight Loss (8:01)[CC] URL
      • Video: The Economics of Seinfeld - What's the Right Gift to Give...Cash? (2:53)[Amara CC] Page

        With Elaine's birthday coming up Jerry has to decide on what to get her. Since they are not in a relationship but they are still having sex he feels that the symbolism of the gift needs to be carefully thought out. He looks for a gift with George but is unable to think of anything, though he vaguely remembers her saying "something about a bench". Elaine is unhappy with the eventual gift: $182 in cash. Jerry's misery is compounded when Kramer gives Elaine the bench she was looking for, for which she is much more grateful.

      • Video: The Office "Not So Secret Santa" (3:25)[Amara CC] Page

        The staff sets up a Secret Santa exchange, but Michael turns it into a Yankee Swap.The "Secret Santas took the time to learn the preferences of the person they are giving a gift to, whereas in the Yankee Swap, some people get stuck with gifts they do not like.

      • Video: Wealth in the Beatles "Taxman" (2:41)[Amara CC] Page

        Imagine being wealthy in a country that significantly taxed high earners.  Would you move to another country like the Beatles?  What would be some reasons to stay?  Might the opportunity cost of moving to another country -- such as immigration hurdles, being far from family, not knowing the language, or not having a job that could transfer to a new country -- outweigh the benefit of lower tax rates?

      • Video: The Deadweight Loss of Gift Giving in the Kinks' "Father Christmas" (3:45)[Amara CC] Page

        Is cash a better gift than a present?

      • Video: Positive Externalities in Seinfeld "The Junior Mints" (4:34)[Amara CC] Page

        Kramer and Jerry go to visit Elaine's ex-boyfriend, who is in the hospital undergoing surgery.  While at the hospital, Kramer persuades Jerry to watch the operation with him in a gallery above the operating theater.  When Kramer sneaks in candy and forces it on Jerry, Jerry knocks Kramer's hand, and a Junior Mint falls from the gallery and lands inside the patient.  The doctor later comments that something "from above" helped the patient stave off an infection.
